segments.text: things special for the recognition and I suppose I was told that because I supported them and so forth and believed in them, which I did.
Now, they always at home football games, where else did they normally appear?
The Fat Stock Show in Houston and they'd go to the Battle of the Flowers in San Antonio and
several times to the Stock Show in Houston, I mean in Fort Worth.
And of course the Corps trips.
Did they go to all Corps trips?
Yes.
And they, now they were not always allowed in to, you know, we had trouble even getting them in the stadium down here because they were
tearing up the track, and we had to put them in booties.
And that was a hassle, and we did it, and they did it.
But they just go all over the place.
I know one year, one of my captains, Captain Jim Holland, and his wife were the Army people that worked with him a lot.
His wife was an equestrian.
Still is.
My other divorce now with Jim.
Jim and his wife did a lot for him.
And Jim came to me one time and said, a lot of them want to take a trail ride this summer.
And so about 15 of them rode down into, almost down into Brownfield.
A 15-day trip.
And of course, I let him go.
That's a duty trip for him.
And they had a good time on that one.
They had Aggies all along the way that fed them and put them up and took care of the horses.
They engineered that thing.
What were the requirements, as far as you were aware, for a student to be in the Mounted Cavalry?
Well, first of all, when I was there, it was the first two things.
You could not be a commander or an RV.
Not that I had anything against them.
It was just that I thought they thought.
Could you be a fish?
Could a freshman?
Oh, we are sophomores.
Sophomores.
And the sophomores could not then and don't now ride.
I mean, I'm sure they ride around out there, but they're not in the parade or anything like that.
And only seniors in the formal appearance of the cow.
I don't think that changed yet.
I think it's still that way.
The juniors are, you know, training for it, but they don't get
Could they be in any branch?
Oh, yes.
Any or none.
Just want to be in and they don't screen them or anything like that.
If you want to be in the cow, you can be in the cow.
You just have to live up to these rules and they spent a lot of time at it.
How did they come up with the official
I've often wondered, why is it called Mounted Cavalry?
There's no other cavalry except Mounted, is there?
Well, I don't know.
Well, I don't know of any, but I guess that's just a...
But isn't that the official name?
Yeah.
Parsons Mounted Cavalry?
Back then, the cavalry was in tanks and so forth.
Of course, when they were here, they were mounted back in the old days.
But...
And we still are, as far as I know.
We're the only mounted unit in the United States, other than Fort Hood.
We're on Fort Riley now and a few other military things.
But I know Buck Henderson and I and my wife, we used to go out with them and cut hay in the summer and that sort of stuff.
And my wife would drive the tractor, and Buck and I would throw bales up there.
We spent a lot of time with them.
We enjoyed it.

And one other thing or two I was thinking about, we used to have cadets over the house once in a while, as many as we could, but one time we had a few of them out there, and just no special ones, just some of the kids.
Anyways, when I was there, I made the comment, I was just talking about my backyard, and I said, God, I wish I had one of those benches like they have at the Grove.
And I should have never said that, because the next morning,
When we got up, there was a bench sitting out in my backyard from the grove, and it had BQ 68 on it, carved in there.
I don't know if that was a fresh carving or not, and I never asked, but I still got that bench, and I never returned it.
So I guess I stole a bench from the university, but that taught me then, don't ever say I wish around those guys, because if they like you, you'll get it.
Were there any goofy things that ever happened to the cavalry?
Oh, I don't know of any.
No jokes, no pranks, no mistakes?
Oh, well, yeah, I'm sure they made lots of those.
What about cleaning up behind?
Oh, well, that's a story.
You know, they always, whenever the scooper, now that wheelbarrow with two U's on it is a brainchild of Buck Henderson and Tom Parsons.
We're the ones that said, hey, let's get them to paint that thing and
following the horse and put the TU in there, and that's kind of an insult to TU.
So I guess I'm responsible for that, and Burke Henderson and I. Yeah, the cleanup crew are those freshmen?
Those are sophomores.
Sophomores.
Right.
Freshmen, there are no freshmen out there.
And they have a, still have a pretty, it's a pretty big, I think it was about $150 semester membership fee.
I mean, you know, it's pretty, it takes a lot of money to go to university
Picks up a good deal of it now.
But the biggest improvement there was when that little shed was put out there with latrine facilities because it was monstrous out there before.
And also the cavalry was the first unit or activity of the A&M to allow a woman in it.
They had a female rider before the RVs or anybody else.
And she was a good rider.
And I can't remember her name right now, but anyway, she was the first.
Were there any problems with that as far as you know?
Well, some of the guys didn't like it too much, but they were accepted, and she rode better than they did, according to doing fritz and everything.
Basically, the members, as far as you recall, were these farm boys or were they city?
I would say more of them from the city had never seen a horse in a ranch, although there were a lot of them, both of them.
But they did, one year they wanted me to troop the land at the parents' day parade and mounted.
And I said, I'm not a horseman, I'm really not.
I'm kind of a little scared of them.
And they said, well, we'll put you on one that you don't have to worry about.
And I said, OK, but I'll do it.
I said, I'm uneasy on him, and just keep that in mind.
So anyway, I went out there one day before the parade, the practice, and they pulled up some steps over there for me.
I said, I ain't that old.
If I can't get on him, I'm not going to get on him.
So I got on him, and I said, now what's his name?
He said, Dynamite.
Dynamite?
You put me on dynamite?
Well, it wasn't dynamite.
They were hassling me.
But anyway, I did that the next day, and it went off all right.
And dynamite almost went to sleep on me while I was going around.
But never again did they ask me to ride.
And I wasn't comfortable with it.
But they still, my wife and I, we go there.
We've only missed a couple of times going out there.
And we have the honor of presenting our saber.
We buy sabers for the new commander.
And we've been doing that for about 25 years.
And they're real appreciative of some of them more than others.
But there was one other story.
We were out there shortly after Grace and I were married.
And she didn't know anything about it.
Never been to any.
Didn't even know what it stood for.
Anyway, I was showing around out to Green, and one of the kids was out there, and I introduced myself as Colonel Parsons.
I went, oh, are you related to the Colonel Parsons that Sal named after him?
I said, yeah, that's me.
He said, oh, I thought he was dead.
So anyway, they know me better than that now.
Describe what the band was in terms of the commandant's concerns.
Well, the band, first of all, I didn't have much influence on the band other than I'm responsible for them being a battery and artillery and infantry band.
That's what it used to be, and I got them to rename it.
I had no problem with anybody except one that was coming out of
He didn't like the idea of changing it.
It was a room band and a white band then.
I just thought it more core to go back to what it used to be.
And the band has always been rambunctious.
And my senior year,
My unit was, I was an A-batter.
We were on the bottom stoop.
I might have told you that yesterday.
There was a band on.
The band had the top three, and that was pretty high.
They were just living.
But I think they were pretty much like they were then.
And I see in your days, it's coming up, all of the band was Army?
No.
Oh, they were?
Whoever.
Oh, okay.
Okay.
And compared to the rest of the Corps, how did the band measure, compare in terms of their grades and their military qualities and so forth?
I don't know much of a distinction.
Some of the top-ranking guys that I knew were in the band, and of course they worked pretty hard, but in the rollers industry, like the fish drill team, my goodness, the things that
happened to them and I'm glad that that's controlled now.
But cadets time is really pretty busy and they all seem to adapt to it.
The band, the rest of the Corps, seemed to be an anti-band most of the time, when they see that band out there on that field.
Is part of that maybe envy, respect, admiration?
Well, I think, look at our Aggie band out there.
I think they get along well, but of course that band drill field was not sacred ground
I didn't even know that after I left here.
I was getting ready to walk across it, and one day when Grace's son, you know, we brought him to A&M, and he'd never been to college.
He was in the Navy, and we talked him into coming in.
He was a B-1 commander, and he said, oh, don't step out there.
And I said, why not?
And they were in that little hut there near there.
He said, man, I'll form you.
Anyway, I don't go in the band field anymore.
We used to have, you know,
played football and all kinds of stuff out there.
Now, Colonel Adams was band director when you got here.
Right.
And did he go all through your years?
No, Joe Haney.
Joe Haney?
He came in before I got to Adams for time.
All right, and describe working with Joe Haney.
Oh, he was
very cooperative.
Colonel Adams, I didn't have a fight.
He'd just been there longer than Ripley.
And he was, you know, he didn't mess with his band.
And I didn't.
He didn't argue a whole lot about it.
He just wanted to know why did I want to change it from green to white.
And I still think it was a good move of him, but there was no big problem.
Fish drill team.
It was here when you got here.
Had there been a fish drill team when you were a cadet?
No.
I don't know when it came about.
It started when they were out at Bryanfield.
Bryanfield, that's right, as a matter of fact.
Bryanfield, of course, happened during my time.
But I never thought much about the fish drill team when I came back.
And I was pretty impressed with the way they operated and the national champions and this, that, and the other.
And Maitland was doing a good job with them.
And I don't hold the statement I'm going to make as maybe not the truth or whatever, but I made a mistake turning over to the Navy Marine program because
Marines have a different outlook on discipline, and I think that's what happened.
And the Army, when we were running the drill team as far as supervision, I'm sure a lot of that stuff still went on, but not near as severely as it was.
And I think that, like I said, I have nothing but admiration for Marines having
gone into Incheon on the third wave behind the Marines.
I was very happy for the Marines, but I'm afraid that's probably what happened to them.
But while you were commandant, were there some hazing problems in the fish drill team?
Well, I knew that they were they were hassling the heck out of them up during their drill period, but I don't know what went on in the military area.
There was probably nothing there because they were
scattered throughout the court.
But I know their training was very disciplined.
What were some, as far as you were aware, while you were commandant, what were some of the examples of the dormitory hazing and pranks and jokes and all that?
What were they doing?
Well, I'm pretty sure that there were occasions when the board was used.
I don't think it was
too often.
I do know of one occasion when they turned some chickens loose in a room over a spring break and turned the heat up.
I'd never heard of that one before, but that was a disaster.
I know one morning, Buck Henderson, who was on my staff then, had been over in the core area and offered me a call.
It was before everybody was there.
I don't know, 7 o'clock in the morning, something like that, and said, Conner, get over to the dorm and live in right now.
Somebody just put saccharine in the commodes in the dorm on the first stoop.
And, of course, we called maintenance people.
By the time I got over there, Buck and I cleaned that concrete out of them toilets.
before it set.
I mean, we were digging in, and that wasn't one of the, I don't guess you normally do that, but we didn't want that stuff to sit in there.
We had a heck of a mess.
Don't know who did it to this date, but we got it out before it set because of the still water.
Drownouts?
I'm sorry?
Were there drownouts?
I just don't know why or who did it or anything.
No, no, no, but were there drownouts going on
Oh, oh, yes, yes, yes.
I don't, I never heard of them having those sticks that were used to barricade, you know the name for them.
Yeah.
Were the, were those not being used, or they were?
They were when I was a student, but not later because they could lock their doors.
Ah.
We were not allowed to lock doors.
That's right, that's right.
And during your days as Commandant, were they going down in the steam tunnels?
Not to my knowledge.
That had been closed off?
I never heard of it.
I never mentioned the tunnels either.
Were there ever any incidents in the dining hall that you had to deal with?
No, not really other than the food throwing, but it wasn't near what it was.
air raids back as what they used to have in my day, and they were pretty bad then.
What about drinking in the dorms?
I'm sure it was there, but it wasn't open.
The problem was beer busts off campus primarily.
Where did they go for those?
I guess they went out to the old, on the other side of the issue, where those
to Quonset Huts where, that's where we found the cannons.
And I think I went out there some, and I don't know whether they ever did that with the cow there or not.
I've never heard of it going on out there, but I don't know.
I just don't know where they're hanging it from.
And y'all didn't have to worry about drugs, did you?
No.
I don't even know if we had any or not.
I don't think there was.
I just wasn't very sophisticated on that until I got to Fort Carson.
Were there girls with, were there guys that brought girls into their rooms?
Was that a problem in the Corps then?
While you were commandant?
It was not, it was pretty rare.
It did happen.
I remember one occasion that I was wandering through the corridor in the morning
four or five o'clock, something like that, and there was a kid tied to a flagpole, you know, in underwear and a mattress cover and chained to it with a handcuff, asking what outfit, and he told me.
I said, I'll get you loose.
And so I went through this outfit and banged on the door, and I'm in the uniform, and the door pulls open, and this guy says, what the F do you want?
lights on and here's a full colonel standing up here and there's a guy on his bed over there.

So I wanted that guy cut loose down there in two minutes and I wanted to see him in my office at 7 a.m. in his dress uniform and anyway he showed up and figured he'd pack his bags and whatever and I just had a follow son chat with him and told him
They were stupid and he was taking a chance for his whole life and I'm not against what they were doing or whatever, but that's not the time and the place.
And he's my friend to this day.
Oh good.
And I've never mentioned his name and never will.
RVs.
What role do the Ross Volunteers play?
Well, you know, they were disbanded during the war.
And they started them back, I believe, you probably know this better than me, I think it was 47.
And they used to drill out there on the band drill field.
And I used to look out my dorm room window and say, look at those idiots out there.
I wasn't in an RV.
And I don't, you know, didn't really want to be one.
for a couple of reasons.
One is I did have that job, and secondly, I couldn't do much sense of going around out there, and I couldn't afford a uniform.
But I did find out I'd been blackballed.
And later found out the reason is, and I don't understand to this day why this guy objected, but I was late dating my roommate's date.
So I imagine that had something to do with it.
But during your days as commandant, the RVs...
I was very impressed with them.
They were quality people.
I never heard of any of them getting in real serious trouble.
And how does somebody become a member of the Ross Volunteers?
Well, of course, they got to have good grades and what translates to about a B average there was.
You know, and the clean record in the corral.
But they have to be voted into it, sort of like a lodge.
And about how many members are there?
Goodness, I don't know, a hundred and some odd.
I don't know for sure.
Juniors and seniors?
Juniors and seniors.
I just don't know.
As far as you're aware, does it matter whether they're Army, Navy, Air Force, Marine?
No difference.
And they select their own commander.
And any junior or senior in the Corps is eligible, including the Corps commander, and all of them can be RVs.
Right, if they meet the minimum grade requirements.
So the RVs would claim to be the cream of the crop?
They claim that, yeah.
And they probably are.
I certainly know the ones I know that were RVs and so forth.
Those are more of them.
acquainted with the Corps of Staff, and they were good kids.
Did you ever have any problems with an RV activity?
No.
During your years as Commandant, who were the key people on your office staff?
Well, you know, I mentioned Don Johnson, and were there some John Adams?
Were there some secretaries?
Well, John Adams later stole my secretary away from me and married her.
Oh.
So, you know, he had been married previously and they were divorced.
And Sherry, who is his wife now, I don't know if you know her or not, she's a lovely gal.
She's a senior secretary out at the vet college.
But he stole her away from the commandant.
But we had one lady there who answered the phone at the receptionist, and she was there when I was a student, so she was kind of hard to get along with.
But the cadets sometimes wanted to see me, and I always told them, unless I got my door closed, you know, you can call me, but that's what I'm here for, you know.
They didn't see me open the door any time.
But what was a, during the normal week, describe a typical day for the commandant.
What time did you get up?
What time did you get to the office?
What did you do?
Well, again, I'm probably not your typical person.
I usually got to the office by 6 in the morning because I'm an early riser and that's just my habit from the military.
And I'd sit around there and go over the,
whatever paperwork I had to do and all that kind of stuff.
And then people started coming in 7.30, 8 o'clock, like that, and started doing business.
And usually some parents would come in during the day wanting to talk about the Corps and print on the schedule and spend a good bit of time with them and walk around with them.
And I met with the Corps commander almost on a daily basis.
If he weren't there, the deputy would come in and we'd talk about, you know, what's going on in the Corps and any problems or something like that.
Usually, most of the time I'd stay for the evening and pass by and wouldn't eat with him.
I'd go home about six o'clock.
Where did you eat lunch normally?
I never ate lunch.
Oh, you didn't?
No.
Right.
And so pass by, then would you go home?
Go home, yeah.
How many, during a normal week, how many nights were busy with campus business?
Not with the Corps, usually the nights, the nights were busy with all these things that you got to show up at, you know.
It seemed like every night you had to do something, and it really got to be a hassle.
And almost every weekend.
Oh yeah, and it's never, never any home time, and it's very bad for a family with children.
Not with even the wife, the wife loved it.
What were, what were you able to do to relax?
Well.
Hobbies, fun?
Of course, it's kind of hard to say.
I'd like to go to the football games and such as that, but I'm still in a sense somewhat duty, but I don't remember a whole lot of free time.
We used to go out to the country western place
But again, the kids were out there too.
I used to like to do that stuff.
And I don't remember any special activities we were in.
It seemed like everything was around the university.
Right.
You served as Commandant from 71 to?
Seven.
Six years.
And that six years was because it was time for you to retire officially?
Well, I was, I had another year I could have stayed on active duty, but there was no way I could stay.
You know, normal tour is three years, extended to four.
And, you know, unknown to me, and I brought the corps responsible for me staying.
I don't know if you know about the petition or not.
The what?
The petition.
No.
This is a, and I didn't know this was going on, believe me.
But they didn't want me to leave, and they found this thing here and gave it to Dr. Williams.
These are all members of the Corps.
Yes, that's the only one.
How marvelous.
And this is dated 1970.
The 100th anniversary.

Therefore, we, the undersigned members of sophomore and junior classes, respectfully request you as our president take steps to renew Colonel Parsons' tour of duty to A&M for another year in order that he might help us have a noteworthy centennial observance of our school.
How did you learn about that?
Dr. Williams called me to his office and laid that on me and says, what do you feel about this?
And I said, well, Dr. Williams, the Army is not going to let me stay.
And he says, how bad do you want it?
I said, I'd love to.
He says, you understand you'll never be a general if you stay.
And I said, I'm probably not going to be a general anyway.
And I said, I've had the time of my life.
And I said, I'm willing to do it if it'll work.
And he said, I think we can work it out.
Well, General Otter, who was my army boss, came down here, and we had a meeting in the president's office.
And General Ludeke also was there.
And he says, Parsons can't stay.
We've got the guy picked out that's going to be this guy.
Dr. Williams said, don't waste my time.
Parsons is going to study, and he's going to be the commandant.
And General Honor said, Marshall, we just can't do it then.
I mean, we won't allow it.
And then Dr. Williams says, do you know who Tiger Teague is?
And anyway, he allowed us.
He'd heard of him.
And Dr. Williams said, I'll be in touch with Tiger Teague.
Well, shortly thereafter, I got a call that I was extended
I was not truly loved by my general.
So that's how it happened, and of course it went into two years, and it was time for me to move on now.
What do you remember about that centennial year?
Well, it was damn busy going to things.
I don't remember too much, but just a lot of activities.
Corps was deeply involved in it, of course.
And during that year, Dr. Williams had his heart attacks.
Yes.
Do you remember hearing about any news about that?
Well, of course, everybody was concerned about it, but not much news.
I was primarily involved in it, and General Simpson was
running things and so on, but he was the pipeline.
I didn't, I used to see Dr. Williams almost daily, but not during the Act of Assumption game.
And how did you feel when Dr. Williams is no longer physically able to be the president?
Well, you know, he was the president during my
period, period.
I wouldn't under any others.
Dr. Miller would not come on the same.
So I can't compare him to any others.
He was just, he was really logical and he was very military oriented and student oriented and I just, I just think he was a wonderful person.
